Chaldaei, ‘astrologers,' called also by Tacitus ‘mathematici’ and ‘periti coelestium.’ This prediction was perhaps the one made by the son of 'Tiberius’ astrologer Thrasyllus (vi 22, 6).

CH. 11, ξ Ι. repetita, ‘harking back to far previous occur- rences.'

consortium imperii, ‘ a partnership in empire‚' meaning a formal recognition of joint sovereignty with Nero, beyond the privileges which she actually enjoyed.

iuraturas in verba: the ordinary ‘sacramentum’ taken by army, senate, and people to the ‘ princeps,' extended in some measure to all the members of the imperial family3 cf. ch. 7, 5: here Agrippina is charged with having aimed at more than this, viz., to receive an independent oath of allegiance co-ordinate with that taken to her son.
